04286nam a22005655i 9780773584310DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19971997xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735843107 a10.1515/97807735843102doi  a(DE-B1597)654652  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aRutland, Barry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGender and Narrativity /cBarry Rutland. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (268 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTextual Analysis, Discourse and Culture ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Telling Difference -- tToward an Epistemology of Gender -- tTelling the Feminine -- tSex, Lies, and Photography: Reading Detective Fiction as Psychoanalysis in Timothy Findley’s The Telling of Lies -- tF(r)ictions: Feminists Re/Writing Narrative -- tThe (W)rite of Passage: From Childhood to Womanhood in Lucy Maud Montgomery’s Emily Novels -- tWriting Toward Absence: Frances Gregg’s The Mystic Leeway -- tParsifal and Semiotic Structuralism -- tAndrogynous Realism in Heinrich von Kleist’s “Die Heilige Cdcilie Oder Die Gewalt Der Musik (Eine Legende)” -- tClough, Claude, Arnold, and Marguerite: Male Heterophobia in Victorian Poetry -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is impossible to imagine a community that is not divided into at least two gender groups. It is equally impossible to imagine a community that does not tell or enact stories. The relationship between these universal aspects of human culture is the mainspring of Gender and Narrativity. From Genesis to Freud, the Western narrative tradition tells the same old story of masculine dominance/feminine subservience as a matter of divine will or natural truth. Here, nine Canadian scholars challenge and interpret this tradition, in effect "re-telling" the story of gender, and themselves intervening in the narrative process. Critical readings from a wide range of literary texts - medieval and modern, European and Canadian - replace abstract theory in these studies, while sociology, anthropology, psychoanalysis, deconstruction and new history are the axes of discussion. This book exemplifies the current range and diversity of Canadian critical writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGender identity in literature. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBohm, Arnd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabriel, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodard, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrattis, J. Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichard, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRutland, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerdon, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWoods, G.A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358431040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773584310423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773584310/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles